rban" and "immigrant" youth, most people are unable to read them as doing so, and instead see the youth as confused, backward, and problematic. By illuminating the discursive practices of identity, this study underscores the need to conceptualize urban, immigrant identities as contradictory, fractured and unresolved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aImmigrantsxEducationzUnited States. 0aMulticultural educationzUnited States. 0aUrban schoolszUnited States. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Multicultural Education. 4aEducation : Teacher Education. 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh1 aBritzman, Deborah P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438430591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438430591/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles